@aleju another common case is the desire to do appearance augmentations, of which should only occur on the pixel data, not the label image.  What is the correct way to handle this case, or is it currently not possible?

If one defines an augmentation for the images with appearance+geometric augmentation sequences, and one for the labels of just appearance, reseeding would yield different random states, as you mention.

Deepcopying augmentation sequences would cause the appearance based augmentations to modify the per-pixel label image.  Would it work to not only modify the order, but also all the appearance parameters to effectively be no-op?  E.g. for GaussianBlur, to set the sigma 0? Would it also be necessary to stay within the same parameter type? E.g. sigma=Custom StochasticParameter -> sigma=iap.Uniform(0,0) and not sigma=0?

You may try the following command line:
```sh
minimap2 --cs -c -k13 -N50 -t8 exon2_3.fasta reads.fastq > aln.paf
```
This uses shorter seeds and does more alignment for accuracy. When counting, you need to account for equally best alignments. From what I see, C\*03:04 appears much more frequently than C\*03:03 as the top hits. You can find a small script at the end. You need k8 (available from minimap2 binary packages) to run. It gives you top alleles. The script just gives you a rough idea.

```js
var min_frac = 0.97;
if (arguments.length == 0) {
    print("Usage: k8 naive-type.js <in.paf>");
    exit(1);
}

var buf = new Bytes();
var file = new File(arguments[0]);

function process_a(a, h) { // a[] keeps the list of alignments for the same read
    var m, max = 0, n_max = 0, b = []; 
    for (var i = 0; i < a.length; ++i) { // parse alignment score (AS)
        var ai = a[i];
        for (var j = 11; j < ai.length; ++j)
            if ((m = /AS:i:(\d+)/.exec(ai[j])) != null)
                b[i] = parseInt(m[1]);
    }   
    for (var i = 0; i < a.length; ++i) // find the max score
        if (b[i] != null)
            max = max > b[i]? max : b[i];
    for (var i = 0; i < a.length; ++i) // count the number of alignments having the max score
        if (b[i] == max)
            ++n_max;
    for (var i = 0; i < a.length; ++i) { // count best alleles
        if (b[i] != max) continue;
        var g = a[i][5];
        if (h[g] == null) h[g] = 1 / n_max;
        else h[g] += 1 / n_max;
    }   
    a.length = 0;
}

var a = [], h = {}; 
while (file.readline(buf) >= 0) {
    var t = buf.toString().split("\t");
    for (var i = 6; i <= 8; ++i)
        t[i] = parseInt(t[i]);
    if (t[8] - t[7] < t[6] * min_frac) continue; // skip poor alignments
    if (a.length && t[0] != a[0][0]) // now we come to a new read
        process_a(a, h); 
    a.push(t);
}
process_a(a, h); 

file.close();
buf.destroy();

var c = []; 
for (var g in h) // get the list of alleles and counts
    c.push([g, h[g]]);
c.sort(function(a,b) {return b[1]-a[1]}); // sort by counts, in the descending order
for (var i = 0; i < c.length; ++i) // print them out
    print(c[i].join("\t"));
```

