I haven't done extensive testing (Just threw this together since my last post here), but this seems to work so far:

`plexToken` is a client token (I.E. ripped from the web traffic of plex.tv/web), not a user token. `X-Plex-Client-Identifier` can be absolutely anything. Also, I don't program in Python, so excuse any issues you may have with the code:

```
import requests
import plexapi
import xml.dom.minidom
from plexapi.myplex import PlexServer

plexToken = "REDACTED";

def plexHttpPost(url):
    plexHeaders = {
            "X-Plex-Token": plexToken,
            "X-Plex-Client-Identifier": "SpongeBobSquarePants"
        };
    plexResponse = requests.post(url, headers=plexHeaders);
    return plexResponse;

def plexHttpGet(url):
    plexHeaders = {
            "X-Plex-Token": plexToken,
            "X-Plex-Client-Identifier": "SpongeBobSquarePants"
        };
    plexResponse = requests.get(url, headers=plexHeaders);
    return plexResponse;

plexUsersXML = plexHttpGet("https://plex.tv/api/home/users");
plexUsers = xml.dom.minidom.parseString(plexUsersXML.text).getElementsByTagName("User");

print("Found {0:d} users!".format(plexUsers.length));

for user in plexUsers:
    print("Processing {0:s} ({1:d})".format(user.getAttribute("title"), int(user.getAttribute("id"))));
    plexUserCredentialsXML = plexHttpPost("https://plex.tv/api/home/users/{0:s}/switch".format(user.getAttribute("id")));
    plexUserCredentials = xml.dom.minidom.parseString(plexUserCredentialsXML.text).getElementsByTagName("user")[0].getAttribute("authenticationToken");
    plexServer = PlexServer("http://redacted:32400", plexUserCredentials);
    tvShows = plexServer.library.section("TV Shows");
    
    for series in tvShows.search(unwatched=False):
        print(series.title);
```

Credit for working out what to send where: https://github.com/ngovil21/Plex-Cleaner/

It'd be nice for plexapi to have the ability to do the above automatically, but if not it's really not the end of the world.

