@aceidon it appears that the API has changed as of this morning. The Share (now Stock, as of 82e85fc) class is structured to download *all* endpoints in a [batch request](https://iextrading.com/developer/docs/#batch-requests) upon instantiation for performance reasons. This required a 19-endpoint (encoded "types") request

> (https://api.iextrading.com/1.0/stock/market/batch?symbols=aapl&types=quote,chart,book,open-close,previous,company,key-stats,peers,relevant,news,financials,earnings,dividends,splits,logo,price,delayed-quote,effective-spread,volume-by-venue)

The change from the provider's end is that only 10-types are now allowed. It seems best to now split the endpoints in two halves and conduct a request for each. It is not necessary to alter to require a request for each endpoint method, as that could significantly increase the number of requests made.

so if I understand correctly you want to have a server side pagination but the sort/filter logic on the client. 

In this case I would not use the custom pipe function but:
1) use st-safe-src attribute to watch the datasource (to update the collection whenever more data is loaded
2) "recreate" the pagination without using the smart-table one. You can for example use [lrInifinteScroll](https://github.com/lorenzofox3/lrInfiniteScroll) to add an event handler whenever the scroll reach the end
and in you event handler you update the watch collection with the loaded data
```Javascript
var page = 1;

this.loadMoreData=function(){
  page++;
  $http.get('/data?page='+page).then(function(result){
     this.rowCollection = this.rowCollection.concat(result.data);
  }.bind(this))
}
```

Even better: you could move the sort/filter logic to your server. I think it is bad user experience to have 
the pagination on the server side and the rest on the client: the result of a sort/filter operation will be different depending on how much data the user has already loaded and this can be misleading

