@pthomas551 In projects using git (and usually other VCS, but this convention came from git AFAIK) commit message looks like

    {commit summary}
    {[empty line]
    commit description}

It is what git itself expects to see in the commit message. `{commit summary}` takes up to 70 unicode codepoints (though usually recommended to use up to 50 display cells, but I do not see it reasonable enough; 70 is because 71’th code point github displays under `…`, 50 is what git help recommends (search for `50` in `git help commit`), most likely due to old terminals’ 80 display cells limitation (needs some space for the commit hash in things like `git log --oneline`).

Note: unicode codepoint, display cell and character are different entities. Git help actually recommends 50 characters, but given why I think it recommends what it recommends it should be “display cell”. “Character” is in any case not a well-defined thing, different people may use it at least either as a synonim to “unicode codepoint” or as a synonim to “grapheme cluster” (code point with all following combining characters: something which is visually displayed as one “character”). Not as a synonim to a “display cell” though, but I do not think anybody will be happy when he will see 50 fullwidth characters in his terminal (they take 100 display cells): https://github.com/ZyX-I/powerline/commits/test-commit-messages, see commit https://github.com/ZyX-I/powerline/commit/214533d7eefd87f6861ac373796e77bf6bf200a8 in this list.

